Programming Language\\\",\\\"url\\\":\\\"https://go.dev/gopls/analyzers\\\"}]\\n\\nBased on the search results, I found comprehensive information about string slicing, byte boundaries, and runes in Go. Here's what the web search revealed:\\n\\n## String Slicing and Byte Boundaries in Go\\n\\nWhen text includes multi-byte characters, indexing raw bytes may not match character boundaries. This is a critical issue when working with Unicode text.\\n\\nWorking directly with bytes is fine for ASCII, but text with multi-byte characters is safer to handle as runes to avoid splitting characters in the middle.\\n\\n## Key Distinctions\\n\\nIn Go, strings are sequences of bytes, not characters. A string in Go is a read-only slice of bytes that is a sequence of bytes representing UTF-8 encoded text.\\n\\n## Rune Handling\\n\\nA rune slice treats each index as a complete Unicode code point, making it ideal for character-aware operations and is the safest way to work with text that may contain symbols, accented letters, or characters from non-Latin scripts.\\n\\n## Go Analysis Tools\\n\\nThe search results indicate that ranging over a string yields byte offsets and runes, and while converting to a slice of runes is functionally equivalent if the offset isn't used, ranging directly over the string is more performant as it avoids allocating a new slice.\\n\\nThese insights are relevant for developing custom linters that detect improper string slicing at invalid byte boundaries in Go code.\\n\\n\\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks.\"}]},\"uuid\":\"dd275de8-600c-4524-94cf-9de3098249c5\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-02-20T12:12:42.166Z\"},\"normalizedMessages\":[],\"type\":\"agent_progress\",\"prompt\":\"Research what Go static analysis tools or linters exist that can detect unsafe byte-based string truncation (slicing strings by byte index which can split multi-byte UTF-8 characters).\\n\\n1. Search the web for Go linters that