utf8/\\\"},{\\\"title\\\":\\\"utf8string package - golang.org/x/exp/utf8string - Go Packages\\\",\\\"url\\\":\\\"https://pkg.go.dev/golang.org/x/exp/utf8string\\\"},{\\\"title\\\":\\\"Strings in Go -Go 101\\\",\\\"url\\\":\\\"https://go101.org/article/string.html\\\"},{\\\"title\\\":\\\"Converting rune slices to strings - Boldly Go\\\",\\\"url\\\":\\\"https://boldlygo.tech/archive/2024-03-08-converting-rune-slices-to-strings/\\\"},{\\\"title\\\":\\\"- The Go Programming Language\\\",\\\"url\\\":\\\"https://go.dev/src/strings/strings.go?s=7164:7198\\\"}]\\n\\nBased on my search results, I found comprehensive information about UTF-8 string handling in Go, particularly related to the key topics in your query.\\n\\n## Key Findings\\n\\n### UTF-8 and String Slicing Issues in Go\\n\\nBecause Go strings are UTF-8 encoded, slicing by index may not work as expected for strings that contain multi-byte characters, such as emojis or accented letters. This is a critical concern for linter and custom rule detection.\\n\\n### Rune Indexing for Safe Operations\\n\\nFor robust, character-aware slicing, convert to []rune first. The proper approach involves understanding that strings are built from bytes so indexing them yields bytes, not characters.\\n\\n### Practical Detection Patterns\\n\\nConverting to rune slice allows safe character access, and developers can use functions like `utf8.DecodeRuneInString()` to properly iterate through UTF-8 encoded strings. Go's byte-oriented approach means string length doesn't equal character count. The len() function returns bytes, not runes.\\n\\n### Custom Rule Implementation\\n\\nFor implementing custom rules in a linter, the standard approach is to avoid slicing at positions that fall in the middle of a multi-byte UTF-8 sequence, as this can result in invalid UTF-8 and replacement characters. For robust, character-aware slicing, convert to []rune first.\\n\\nThe search results contain practical code examples and utilities in the Go standard library (`unicode/utf8` package) that linters can use to detect improper string handling patterns.\\n\\n\\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks.\"}]},\"uuid\":\"e16d3223-ff24-42fc-8bbd-93a1dea637d3\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-02-20T12:12:52.931Z\"},\"normalizedMessages\":[],\"type\":\"agent_progress\",\"prompt\":\"Research what Go static analysis tools or linters exist that can detect unsafe byte-based string truncation (slicing strings by byte index which can split multi-byte UTF-8 characters).\\n\\n1. Search the web for Go linters that detect UTF-8 unsafe string operations, byte-based string slicing, mojibake prevention, etc. Check if any golangci-lint compatible linters exist for this.\\n\\n2. Specifically look for:\\n   - Any existing golangci-lint linter that catches `str[:n]` patterns on strings\\n   - Tools like `go vet` analyzers for UTF-8 safety\\n   - Custom static analysis tools (e.g., based on `golang.org/x/tools/go/analysis`)\\n   - Whether `gocritic`, `staticcheck`, `gosec`, or any common linter has checks for this\\n\\n3. Also check if `forbidigo` (which is already used in the project's .golangci.yaml) could be configured to flag patterns like byte-based string slicing.\\n\\nBe thorough in your web research.\",\"agentId\":\"a4f0dda\"},\"toolUseID\":\"agent_msg_01GxPsXFQ933GHCEUz8wUZSj\",\"parentToolUseID\":\"toolu_01QJXHxrPnawzc3RcUAiJXb9\",\"uuid\":\"a19e5286-70a1-457c-bdd8-4d2a0146d819\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-02-20T12:12:52.932Z\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"a19e5286-70a1-457c-bdd8-4d2a0146d819\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/robin/Developer/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"46b4ee03-63fe-4245-b506-7ab194cf340c\",\"version\":\"2.1.49\",\"gitBranch\":\"fix/utf8-safe-string-truncation\",\"slug\":\"deep-leaping-hinton\",\"type\":\"progress\",\"data\":{\"message\":{\"type\":\"assistant\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-02-20T12:12:54.720Z\",\"message\":{\"model\":\"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001\"