\":\\\"Settings – Golangci-lint\\\",\\\"url\\\":\\\"https://golangci-lint.run/docs/linters/configuration/\\\"},{\\\"title\\\":\\\"Linter: gosec, Rule: G101 - Look for hard coded credentials. Should we enable it? · Issue #12889 · influxdata/telegraf\\\",\\\"url\\\":\\\"https://github.com/influxdata/telegraf/issues/12889\\\"},{\\\"title\\\":\\\"Linter: gosec, Rule: G202 - SQL query construction using string concatenation. Should we enable it? · Issue #12903 · influxdata/telegraf\\\",\\\"url\\\":\\\"https://github.com/influxdata/telegraf/issues/12903\\\"},{\\\"title\\\":\\\"How to fix the \\\\\\\"G101: Potential hardcoded credentials (gosec)\\\\\\\"\\\",\\\"url\\\":\\\"https://blog.skopow.ski/how-to-fix-the-g101-potential-hardcoded-credentials-gosec\\\"}]\\n\\nBased on the search results, here's information about gosec, the Go security linter:\\n\\n## Overview\\n\\nGosec is a free, open-source security linter for Go that scans Go source code using AST and SSA analysis to detect 50+ vulnerability types, each mapped to CWE identifiers. With over 8,700 GitHub stars, it has become the most adopted SAST scanner in the Go ecosystem.\\n\\n## Analysis Approach\\n\\nGosec parses Go source code into an Abstract Syntax Tree, then performs Static Single Assignment analysis to track how data flows through your program, with this two-pass approach catching security issues that pattern matching alone would miss.\\n\\n## Key Features\\n\\nGosec includes SSA-based analyzers for type conversions, slice bounds, and crypto issues, plus taint analysis for tracking data flow from user input to dangerous functions (SQL injection, command injection, path traversal, SSRF, XSS, log injection).\\n\\nGosec detects hardcoded credentials (G101), SQL injection (G201/G202), command injection (G204), weak cryptography like MD5 and DES (G401/G405), insecure TLS settings (G402), weak RSA keys under 2048 bits (G403), path traversal (G304), zip slip (G305), and exposed pprof endpoints (G108), among others.\\n\\n## UTF-8 String Slicing\\n\\nThe search results don't specifically mention a UTF-8 string slicing security check rule in gosec. If you're looking for information about a specific UTF-8 handling rule, you may want to check the [official gosec GitHub repository](https://github.com/securego/gosec) for the complete list of available rules and their documentation.\\n\\n\\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks.\"}]},\"uuid\":\"ad50f3ec-ae34-44fc-8677-a3dd9f3e89ca\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-02-20T12:13:02.854Z\"},\"normalizedMessages\":[],\"type\":\"agent_progress\",\"prompt\":\"Research what Go static analysis tools or linters exist that can detect unsafe byte-based string truncation (slicing strings by byte index which can split multi-byte UTF-8 characters).\\n\\n1. Search the web for Go linters that detect UTF-8 unsafe string operations, byte-based string slicing, mojibake prevention, etc. Check if any golangci-lint compatible linters exist for this.\\n\\n2. Specifically look for:\\n   - Any existing golangci-lint linter that catches `str[:n]` patterns on strings\\n   - Tools like `go vet` analyzers for UTF-8 safety\\n   - Custom static analysis tools (e.g., based on `golang.org/x/tools/go/analysis`)\\n   - Whether `gocritic`, `staticcheck`, `gosec`, or any common linter has checks for this\\n\\n3. Also check if `forbidigo` (which is already used in the project's .golangci.yaml) could be configured to flag patterns like byte-based string slicing.\\n\\nBe thorough in your web research.\",\"agentId\":\"a4f0dda\"},\"toolUseID\":\"agent_msg_01GxPsXFQ933GHCEUz8wUZSj\",\"parentToolUseID\":\"toolu_01QJXHxrPnawzc3RcUAiJXb9\",\"uuid\":\"7817048f-61e1-4892-be5f-f4a76ad6cb4a\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-02-20T12:13:02.857Z\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"7817048f-61e1-4892-be5f-f4a76ad6cb4a\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/robin/Developer/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"46b4ee03-63fe-4245-b506-7ab194cf340c\",