reenplace.net/2021/rewriting-go-source-code-with-ast-tooling/\\\"},{\\\"title\\\":\\\"Golang: String, rune and byte. Golang has no data type for character… | by Claire Lee | Medium\\\",\\\"url\\\":\\\"https://yuminlee2.medium.com/go-string-rune-and-byte-efd2aa6034f6\\\"},{\\\"title\\\":\\\"GitHub - orbs-network/go-ast-trace: Advanced tracing and debugging toolkit for Go language based on AST source injection\\\",\\\"url\\\":\\\"https://github.com/orbs-network/go-ast-trace\\\"}]\\n\\nThe search results provide information about byte indexing, rune boundaries, and Go AST analysis tools. Here's what I found:\\n\\n## Byte Index and Rune Boundary Detection in Go\\n\\nIn Go, strings are built from a sequence of bytes rather than characters, which means text with accented letters, symbols, or emojis doesn't line up neatly with byte indexes, as UTF-8 encoding lets each character take a variable number of bytes.\\n\\n### Key Concepts:\\n\\n**Runes vs. Bytes**: A rune is an alias for int32 and represents a single Unicode code point, and is used in Go to handle characters that may span more than one byte in UTF-8.\\n\\n**For-Range Loop Behavior**: A for range loop decodes one UTF-8-encoded rune on each iteration, with the index of the loop being the starting position of the current rune, measured in bytes.\\n\\n### Go AST Analysis Tools\\n\\nGo is well-known for having great tooling for analyzing code written in the language, right in the standard library with the go/* packages (go/parser, go/ast, go/types etc.); in addition, the golang.org/x/tools module contains several supplemental packages that are even more powerful.\\n\\nOne practical tool available is go-ast-trace, which works by manipulating the source code of your program and injecting logging commands directly inside, relying on golang's ability to parse golang sources to AST, manipulate the AST and then print it back to source code.\\n\\n\\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user us