ead by every byte. This is important when using slice notation like `string[:n]` in Go.\\n\\n**Pattern Analysis Tools:**\\nThe search found the xstrings package which provides string algorithms not included in the strings package. This package includes pattern-based operations for rune manipulation, including translating strings with characters defined in from replaced by characters defined in to, where from and to are patterns representing a set of characters.\\n\\n**Handling Multi-byte Characters:**\\nSince Go strings are UTF-8 encoded, multi-byte characters may need special handling, and runes provide this by representing characters irrespective of their byte-length.\\n\\nThe search results suggest that working with `string[:n]` requires careful consideration of whether you're slicing by bytes or by runes, since runes can be 1-4 bytes each in UTF-8 encoding.\\n\\n\\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks.\"}]},\"uuid\":\"4c07c5d0-2be1-4da6-9574-6b75e9f54f49\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-02-20T12:13:41.261Z\"},\"normalizedMessages\":[],\"type\":\"agent_progress\",\"prompt\":\"Research what Go static analysis tools or linters exist that can detect unsafe byte-based string truncation (slicing strings by byte index which can split multi-byte UTF-8 characters).\\n\\n1. Search the web for Go linters that detect UTF-8 unsafe string operations, byte-based string slicing, mojibake prevention, etc. Check if any golangci-lint compatible linters exist for this.\\n\\n2. Specifically look for:\\n   - Any existing golangci-lint linter that catches `str[:n]` patterns on strings\\n   - Tools like `go vet` analyzers for UTF-8 safety\\n   - Custom static analysis tools (e.g., based on `golang.org/x/tools/go/analysis`)\\n   - Whether `gocritic`, `staticcheck`, `gosec`, or any common linter has checks for this\\n\\n3. Also check if `forbidigo` (which is already used in the project's .golangci.yaml) could be configured to flag patt